INSERT INTO public.service_agreement_templates (name, description, sections, sort_order)
VALUES (
  'Software Development — Split Ownership',
  'Source code and platform infrastructure owned by Shoothill (licence granted to client); product brand IP and customer-specific assets assigned to client. Suitable for collaborative product builds.',
  '[{"heading":"1. Interpretation","body":"1.1  Definitions\n\nIn this Agreement, the following terms shall have the meanings set out below:\n\nApplicable Laws — All applicable laws, statutes and regulations from time to time in force, including but not limited to UK GDPR and the Data Protection Act 2018.\n\nBusiness Day — A day other than a Saturday, Sunday or public holiday in England, when banks in London are open for business.\n\nCharges — The fees and sums payable for the Services as set out in Schedule 2 of this Agreement.\n\nCommencement Date — The date on which this Agreement becomes effective, as specified in Schedule 1.\n\nConfidential Information — All information of commercial value in whatever form disclosed by one Party to the other, including technical, commercial, financial, strategic, product and customer information.\n\nCustomer Data — Data and information inputted by the Customer or its authorised users in connection with the Services.\n\nDeliverables — Any outputs, works or materials to be delivered by the Supplier to the Customer as set out in Schedule 1.\n\nIntellectual Property Rights — Patents, rights to inventions, copyright, trade marks, database rights, rights in designs, rights in computer software, know-how and all other intellectual property rights whether registered or unregistered.\n\nNormal Service Hours — 09:00 to 17:30 GMT, Monday to Friday, excluding English public holidays.\n\nServices — The services to be provided by the Supplier to the Customer as described in Schedule 1 of this Agreement.\n\nTerm — The duration of this Agreement as specified in Schedule 1.\n\n1.2  General Rules of Interpretation\n\nReferences to a statute or statutory provision include all amendments, extensions and re-enactments. Words in the singular include the plural and vice versa. Any words following \"including\", \"include\", \"in particular\" or \"for example\" are illustrative only. \"Writing\" and \"written\" excludes fax but not email. Clause and Schedule headings do not affect interpretation."},{"heading":"2. Services","body":"The scope of the Services, Deliverables, timescales and any applicable project phases are set out in Schedule 1, which is populated from the Supplier''s Proposal and forms an integral part of this Agreement.\n\n2.1  The Supplier shall use reasonable skill and expertise to provide the Services in accordance with this Agreement and Schedule 1.\n\n2.2  The Supplier shall use its reasonable endeavours to meet any performance dates or milestones specified in Schedule 1, but any such dates are estimates only and time shall not be of the essence unless expressly stated otherwise in Schedule 1.\n\n2.3  The Supplier shall notify the Customer in advance of any planned maintenance or service interruptions that may affect the Services.\n\n2.4  The Supplier shall appoint a named Supplier Representative who shall be the primary point of contact for the Customer and shall have responsibility for the overall delivery of the Services.\n\n2.5  Any services not expressly described in Schedule 1 are outside the scope of this Agreement. Additional services may be agreed and added by way of written variation in accordance with clause 6."},{"heading":"3. Customer''s Obligations","body":"3.1  The Customer shall co-operate fully with the Supplier in all matters relating to the Services, and shall appoint a Customer Representative who has authority to bind the Customer on matters relating to the Services.\n\n3.2  The Customer shall provide, in a timely manner, all information, materials, access to premises, systems and personnel reasonably required by the Supplier to perform the Services.\n\n3.3  The Customer shall ensure all information provided to the Supplier is accurate and complete in all material respects. If the Supplier''s performance is delayed or prevented by the Customer''s acts or omissions, the Customer shall be liable for any reasonable additional costs incurred by the Supplier as a result.\n\n3.4  The Customer shall ensure that its systems, equipment and facilities are in good working order and meet any technical specifications notified by the Supplier.\n\n3.5  The Customer shall comply with the Supplier''s Mandatory Policies as set out in Schedule 4, as updated from time to time by notification.\n\n3.6  The Customer shall not, without the Supplier''s prior written consent, allow any third party to modify, maintain or repair any software or deliverables provided by the Supplier under this Agreement."},{"heading":"4. Charges and Payment","body":"The Charges payable for the Services are set out in Schedule 2. The following payment terms apply:\n\n4.1  All invoices are payable within 30 days of the date of invoice unless an alternative payment schedule is specified in Schedule 2.\n\n4.2  All Charges are exclusive of VAT, which shall be charged at the applicable rate. The Supplier shall provide a valid VAT invoice.\n\n4.3  If the Customer fails to pay any sum by the due date, the Supplier may: (a) charge interest at 5% per annum above the Bank of England base rate, accruing daily from the due date until payment in full; and (b) suspend the Services until all outstanding sums are paid.\n\n4.4  All sums shall be paid without set-off, counterclaim, deduction or withholding save as required by law.\n\n4.5  The Supplier may increase the monthly Charges for ongoing services by giving the Customer at least three months'' prior written notice.\n\n4.6  Reasonable out-of-pocket expenses, evidenced in writing, may be charged in addition to the Charges where not already included in Schedule 2.\n\n4.7  Where Services are provided on a time and materials basis, charges shall be calculated at the Supplier''s standard day rates then in force, based on a 7.5-hour working day between 09:00 and 17:30 on Business Days. The current standard day rate is £850 + VAT unless otherwise specified in Schedule 2."},{"heading":"5. Term and Duration","body":"5.1  This Agreement shall commence on the Commencement Date and shall continue for the Initial Term as specified in Schedule 1, unless terminated earlier in accordance with clause 9.\n\n5.2  Where ongoing services are provided (such as support, hosting or maintenance), this Agreement shall automatically renew for successive periods equal to the Initial Term unless either Party gives written notice to the other at least 90 days before the end of the then-current term.\n\n5.3  Fixed-price project engagements shall continue until all Works and obligations have been completed or the Agreement is otherwise terminated in accordance with its terms."},{"heading":"6. Change Control","body":"6.1  Either Party may request changes to the scope or execution of the Services by giving written notice to the other Party.\n\n6.2  Within seven Business Days of receiving a change request, the Supplier shall provide a written estimate of: (a) any increase or decrease in Charges; (b) the likely effect on timescales; and (c) any other impact on this Agreement.\n\n6.3  No change shall take effect until both Parties have agreed it in writing by way of a signed Change Agreement. The Supplier is under no obligation to proceed with any change until such agreement is reached.\n\n6.4  Any additional development work required outside of the agreed scope shall be charged at the Supplier''s applicable day rate as specified in Schedule 2."},{"heading":"7. Intellectual Property","body":"7.1  The Parties acknowledge that different categories of Intellectual Property Rights in the Deliverables are owned differently as set out in this clause.\n\n7.2  Source Code and Platform: All Intellectual Property Rights in any source code, platform components, frameworks and software infrastructure developed by the Supplier shall remain vested in and owned by the Supplier. Subject to full payment, the Supplier grants the Customer a perpetual, non-exclusive, non-transferable licence to use such elements solely to operate the agreed Deliverables for the Customer''s internal business purposes.\n\n7.3  Product and Brand IP: All Intellectual Property Rights in the Customer''s brand elements, product design, customer-facing content and unique business logic specifically created for the Customer (as identified in Schedule 1) shall be assigned to the Customer with full title guarantee upon receipt of full payment of all Charges due under this Agreement.\n\n7.4  The Supplier shall at all times retain ownership of its pre-existing materials, tools, know-how and methodologies, and any generic reusable components not specifically developed for the Customer.\n\n7.5  The Customer grants the Supplier a non-exclusive, royalty-free licence to use the Customer''s materials, data and intellectual property solely to the extent necessary to provide the Services.\n\n7.6  The Supplier retains the right to reference the Customer as a client and to include anonymised or attributed descriptions of the project in its portfolio and marketing materials, unless the Customer objects in writing."},{"heading":"8. Confidentiality","body":"8.1  Each Party undertakes to keep the other Party''s Confidential Information confidential and not to use it other than for the purpose of performing its obligations or exercising its rights under this Agreement (the \"Permitted Purpose\").\n\n8.2  Each Party may disclose the other Party''s Confidential Information to its employees, contractors and professional advisers who need to know it for the Permitted Purpose, provided such persons are bound by obligations of confidentiality no less stringent than those in this clause.\n\n8.3  The obligations in this clause shall not apply to information that: (a) is or becomes public knowledge other than through a breach of this Agreement; (b) was already known to the receiving Party prior to disclosure; (c) is lawfully received from a third party free of restriction; or (d) is required to be disclosed by law or regulatory authority.\n\n8.4  On termination or expiry of this Agreement, each Party shall promptly return or destroy all Confidential Information of the other Party and, if required, certify in writing that it has done so.\n\n8.5  The obligations in this clause shall survive termination or expiry of this Agreement for a period of two years."},{"heading":"9. Termination","body":"9.1  Termination for Cause\n\nEither Party may terminate this Agreement with immediate effect by written notice if the other Party:\n\n(a) fails to pay any sum due under this Agreement within 14 days of being notified in writing to make such payment;\n(b) commits a material breach of this Agreement which, if remediable, it fails to remedy within 30 days of written notice specifying the breach;\n(c) repeatedly breaches any term of this Agreement such that its conduct is inconsistent with having the intention or ability to comply;\n(d) becomes insolvent, is unable to pay its debts as they fall due, enters administration, receivership or liquidation, or takes steps to do so; or\n(e) any warranty given in this Agreement is found to be materially untrue or misleading.\n\n9.2  Termination for Convenience\n\n9.2.1  The Supplier may terminate this Agreement at any time on not less than 3 months'' written notice to the Customer.\n\n9.3  Consequences of Termination\n\n9.3.1  On termination or expiry, the Customer shall immediately pay all outstanding invoices and interest. The Supplier may invoice for Services performed but not yet invoiced, payable immediately on receipt.\n\n9.3.2  Each Party shall promptly return or destroy the other Party''s Confidential Information and, on request, certify in writing that it has done so.\n\n9.3.3  The Customer shall permanently delete or return any proprietary software or materials belonging to the Supplier, and provide written confirmation within 14 days.\n\n9.3.4  If the Customer requires the Supplier to assist with handover to an alternative provider, such work shall be charged at the Supplier''s current day rate, capped at £15,000 + VAT.\n\n9.4  Early Termination Payment\n\nIf the Customer terminates for convenience under clause 9.2.2, or if the Supplier terminates due to any event in clause 9.1, the Customer shall pay to the Supplier an Early Termination Payment equal to all fees properly due for Services performed up to the effective date of termination, less any amounts already paid.\n\n9.5  Survival\n\nTermination shall not affect any rights, remedies, obligations or liabilities accrued up to the date of termination. Clauses 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12 and 14 shall survive termination."},{"heading":"10. Data Protection","body":"10.1  Both Parties shall comply with all applicable data protection laws including the UK General Data Protection Regulation (UK GDPR) and the Data Protection Act 2018.\n\n10.2  Where the Supplier processes personal data on behalf of the Customer in connection with the Services, the Supplier shall act as a data processor and the Customer shall act as a data controller. Details of the processing are set out in Schedule 5.\n\n10.3  The Supplier shall: (a) process personal data only on the documented instructions of the Customer; (b) implement appropriate technical and organisational security measures; (c) ensure personnel engaged in processing are bound by obligations of confidentiality; (d) notify the Customer without undue delay of any personal data breach; (e) assist the Customer in responding to data subject rights requests; and (f) on termination, delete or return all personal data as directed.\n\n10.4  The Customer warrants that it has all necessary consents and notices in place to enable the lawful transfer of personal data to the Supplier.\n\n10.5  The Supplier may appoint sub-processors provided it informs the Customer of any intended changes and ensures sub-processors are bound by equivalent data protection obligations."},{"heading":"11. Warranties","body":"11.1  The Supplier warrants that: (a) it will perform the Services with reasonable skill and care, in accordance with Good Industry Practice; (b) it has the right to enter into this Agreement and to provide the Services; (c) to the best of its knowledge, the Deliverables will not infringe any third-party intellectual property rights; and (d) it will comply with all applicable laws in performing its obligations.\n\n11.2  The Customer warrants that: (a) it has authority to enter into this Agreement; (b) it will comply with all applicable laws in connection with its use of the Services; and (c) it will not introduce any malware, viruses or vulnerabilities into any systems of the Supplier.\n\n11.3  Except as expressly stated in this Agreement, all warranties, representations, conditions and terms implied by statute or common law are excluded to the fullest extent permitted by law.\n\n11.4  The Supplier does not warrant that the Services will be uninterrupted or error-free, or that all Defects will be remedied within specific timeframes."},{"heading":"12. Limitation of Liability","body":"12.1  Nothing in this Agreement limits either Party''s liability for: (a) death or personal injury caused by negligence; (b) fraud or fraudulent misrepresentation; or (c) any other liability that cannot be excluded by law.\n\n12.2  Subject to clause 12.1, the Supplier shall not be liable for: (a) loss of profits; (b) loss of business or business opportunities; (c) loss or corruption of data; (d) loss of anticipated savings; (e) damage to reputation or goodwill; (f) losses arising from defects in third-party software; or (g) any indirect or consequential losses, however caused.\n\n12.3  Subject to clause 12.1, the Supplier''s total aggregate liability under or in connection with this Agreement (whether in contract, tort, negligence, breach of statutory duty or otherwise) shall be limited to the greater of £5,000 and the total Charges paid by the Customer during the 12 months preceding the date on which the claim arose.\n\n12.4  The Customer shall be solely responsible for any decisions, actions or conclusions made on the basis of outputs generated through the Services."},{"heading":"13. Indemnity","body":"13.1  The Customer shall defend, indemnify and hold harmless the Supplier against all claims, losses, damages and costs (including reasonable legal fees) arising from: (a) the Customer''s breach of this Agreement; (b) the Customer''s breach of any third-party licence; (c) the Customer''s negligence or wilful misconduct; or (d) the Customer''s use of the Services in a manner not authorised by this Agreement.\n\n13.2  The Supplier shall defend the Customer against any claim that the use of the Deliverables by the Customer in accordance with this Agreement infringes any United Kingdom intellectual property right, provided the Supplier is given prompt notice of the claim, sole authority to defend it and reasonable co-operation by the Customer."},{"heading":"14. Non-Solicitation","body":"The Customer shall not, without the Supplier''s prior written consent, at any time during this Agreement or for 12 months after its termination or expiry, solicit, entice away, employ or attempt to employ any person who is, or has been, engaged as an employee, consultant or subcontractor of the Supplier in connection with the Services. Any consent to employ such a person shall be subject to the Customer paying to the Supplier a sum equivalent to 20% of that person''s then current annual remuneration."},{"heading":"15. Force Majeure","body":"Neither Party shall be in breach of this Agreement or liable for any delay or failure in performance of its obligations to the extent that such delay or failure results from causes beyond its reasonable control, including but not limited to acts of God, pandemic, war, civil unrest, government action, or failure of utilities or telecommunications networks. The affected Party shall notify the other Party promptly. If the delay continues for more than four weeks, the unaffected Party may terminate this Agreement on seven days'' written notice."},{"heading":"16. General","body":"16.1  Entire Agreement\nThis Agreement (together with the Schedules and any documents referred to in them) constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties and supersedes all prior agreements, representations and understandings relating to its subject matter. Each Party acknowledges that it has not relied on any statement or representation not set out in this Agreement.\n\n16.2  Variation\nNo variation to this Agreement shall be effective unless agreed in writing and signed by authorised representatives of both Parties.\n\n16.3  Waiver\nNo failure or delay in exercising any right or remedy shall constitute a waiver of that right or remedy. A waiver is only effective if given in writing.\n\n16.4  Severance\nIf any provision of this Agreement is or becomes invalid, illegal or unenforceable, it shall be modified to the minimum extent necessary to make it valid and enforceable. If such modification is not possible, the provision shall be deleted. This shall not affect the validity of the remaining provisions.\n\n16.5  Assignment\nThe Supplier may assign or subcontract any of its rights and obligations under this Agreement to a member of its group or to any person to which it transfers its business, provided it gives prior written notice to the Customer. The Customer shall not assign, transfer or deal in any other manner with its rights or obligations without the Supplier''s prior written consent.\n\n16.6  No Partnership or Agency\nNothing in this Agreement shall create a partnership or joint venture between the Parties, or authorise either Party to act as agent for the other.\n\n16.7  Third Party Rights\nThis Agreement does not give rise to any rights under the Contracts (Rights of Third Parties) Act 1999.\n\n16.8  Counterparts\nThis Agreement may be executed in any number of counterparts, each of which shall be an original, and all counterparts together shall constitute one agreement. Transmission of an executed counterpart by email shall take effect as a \"wet ink\" signature."},{"heading":"17. Dispute Resolution","body":"17.1  Any dispute shall be deemed to have arisen when one Party serves written notice on the other specifying the nature of the dispute.\n\n17.2  Within seven days of the notice, the Parties'' project representatives shall meet to attempt to resolve the dispute.\n\n17.3  If not resolved within seven days of that meeting, a director of each Party shall meet within a further seven days to attempt settlement.\n\n17.4  If no settlement is reached, the Parties shall, for a period of 28 days, attempt mediation by an independent mediator with costs shared equally.\n\n17.5  If mediation fails, the dispute shall be referred to the exclusive jurisdiction of the courts of England and Wales.\n\n17.6  During any dispute, the Supplier shall continue to perform its obligations and the Customer shall continue to make undisputed payments."},{"heading":"18. Notices","body":"Any notice under this Agreement shall be in writing and shall be delivered by hand, pre-paid first-class post to the Party''s registered office, or by email to the addresses specified in the execution block below. Notice shall be deemed received: (a) if delivered by hand, at time of delivery; (b) if posted, at 09:00 on the second Business Day after posting; (c) if by email, at the time of confirmed transmission during Normal Service Hours, or when Normal Service Hours resume if sent outside those hours."},{"heading":"19. Governing Law and Jurisdiction","body":"This Agreement and any dispute or claim arising out of or in connection with it (including non-contractual disputes or claims) shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the law of England and Wales. The Parties irrevocably submit to the exclusive jurisdiction of the courts of England and Wales."},{"heading":"Schedule 4 — Mandatory Policies","body":"The Customer shall comply with the following Shoothill policies, as amended from time to time and published at www.shoothill.com:\n\n- Modern Slavery and Human Trafficking Policy\n- Corporate and Social Responsibility / Sustainability Policy\n- Data and Privacy Policy\n- Ethics and Anti-Bribery Policy\n- Breach Response Policy"},{"heading":"Schedule 5 — Data Protection","body":"This Schedule applies where the Supplier processes personal data on behalf of the Customer.\n\nPart A — Role of the Parties\nSupplier acts as: Processor on behalf of the Customer (Controller) in respect of Customer Personal Data processed under this Agreement.\n\nPart B — Particulars of Processing\nSubject Matter: Provision of the Services described in Schedule 1.\nDuration: The Term of this Agreement plus any period required for return or deletion of personal data.\nNature of Processing: Access, storage, hosting, support, maintenance and technical operations as required to deliver the Services.\nPurpose: Performance of the Services and provision of related technical support to the Customer.\n\nSub-Processors\nThe Supplier may engage sub-processors to assist with delivery of the Services. The Supplier shall ensure all sub-processors are bound by data protection obligations no less stringent than those in this Agreement, and shall remain responsible for their acts and omissions. The Supplier shall notify the Customer of any intended changes to sub-processors.\n\nInternational Transfers\nPersonal data shall not be transferred outside the United Kingdom except in accordance with the applicable provisions of UK GDPR and any relevant adequacy decisions, standard contractual clauses or other approved transfer mechanisms."}]'::jsonb,
  3
);
;